                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="20072" author="juergen.hoeller" created="Wed, 4 Oct 2006 23:01:32 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Thanks for pointing this out! I agree that &quot;onTearDownAfterTransaction&quot; should be called even if the transaction has been manually completed before teardown. I&apos;ve changed this for Spring 2.0.1; it&apos;s also gonna be available in tonight&apos;s 2.0.1 snapshot (&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.springframework.org/snapshots&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;http://www.springframework.org/snapshots&lt;/a&gt;).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;As for &quot;onTearDownInTransaction&quot;: Here it&apos;s arguably more correct if this is really only invoked for a transaction that is still active. Else, such teardown code would run outside of the intended context (which implies an active transaction, else you could just as well as put the code in &quot;onTearDownAfterTransaction&quot;).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Juergen&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="20073" author="mrgcos" created="Wed, 4 Oct 2006 23:12:57 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Thanks for the quick response, I&apos;ll download the snapshot tomorrow.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Gordon.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="20075" author="juergen.hoeller" created="Wed, 4 Oct 2006 23:58:05 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Slight refinement: We only call &quot;onTearDownAfterTransaction&quot; if at least one transaction has been started and completed before. If a test calls &quot;preventTransaction()&quot; or doesn&apos;t specify a transaction manager (for whatever reason), neither &quot;onSetUpBeforeTransaction&quot; nor &quot;onTearDownAfterTransaction&quot; will be called, since there is no actual transaction in this case.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Juergen&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
